# Cloudflare Pages static-asset header rules.
#
# Cloudflare Pages reads this file at build time and turns each block
# into edge-layer `Cache-Control` / other headers for the matching
# path. Rules cascade top-to-bottom; later blocks can override earlier
# ones for the same path.
#
# Reference: https://developers.cloudflare.com/pages/configuration/headers/


# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# config.json — the AirTok app's remote feature-flag + version-gate
# feed. Consumed by every client on startup and every 60 s thereafter
# (see `app/lib/providers/remote_config_provider.dart` and
# `app/lib/widgets/version_gate.dart`).
#
# Why a short Cache-Control:
#
#   Default Pages behavior caches static JSON aggressively (minutes
#   to hours). That's fine for privacy.html but WRONG for config.json
#   — a force-update push or a monetization flip is an "immediate"
#   operation from our perspective. With the default cache we'd have
#   to either manually purge from the Cloudflare dashboard after
#   every push (fragile), or accept hours of delay (unacceptable for
#   hotfixes).
#
#   max-age=60 means the CF edge caches the file for at most 60
#   seconds. Combined with the client-side 60 s retry, the worst-case
#   propagation delay is ~2 minutes — good enough for "we pushed a
#   fix, it's live now" without the operator having to do anything
#   extra.
#
#   must-revalidate belts-and-suspenders: any intermediate proxy or
#   OS-level HTTP cache that misinterprets max-age still has to
#   re-check with origin when stale, instead of serving stale copies
#   indefinitely.
#
# Emergency bypass: if you push a broken config and need instant
# rollback, Cloudflare dashboard → airtokapp.com domain → Caching
# → Purge by URL → `https://airtokapp.com/config.json`.
/config.json
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=60, must-revalidate
